<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-08-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-08-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="667" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d667">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-08-22"><hi rend="italic">August 22,
                                1905</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 8. Montenegrin series.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that the
                            Official Gazette of Montenegro published a few days ago a decree of the
                            Prince authorizing a parliament, which will probably meet next December
                            for the first time, and also granting freedom of the press. Until now
                            the legislative power in Montenegro has been in the hands of a council
                            of state, consisting of the crown prince, the metropolitan, and the
                            members of the cabinet. …</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles S.
                            Wilson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>